Milestone Report

The goal of this project is to construct an app to predicts the next word to be typed by a user based on previous ones. In this report, we cover exploratory analysis of the dataset, starting from processing the data and concluding with strategies to simplify our model-building to folow.

Initial Processing

First, let’s look at some basic information about the dataset. How large are the input files? We can print out the total lines and characters in each:

wc -l ./data/en_US/en_US.blogs.txt
wc -l ./data/en_US/en_US.news.txt
wc -l ./data/en_US/en_US.twitter.txt
wc -c ./data/en_US/en_US.blogs.txt
wc -c ./data/en_US/en_US.news.txt
wc -c ./data/en_US/en_US.twitter.txt
## 899288 ./data/en_US/en_US.blogs.txt
## 1010242 ./data/en_US/en_US.news.txt
## 2360148 ./data/en_US/en_US.twitter.txt
## 210160014 ./data/en_US/en_US.blogs.txt
## 205811889 ./data/en_US/en_US.news.txt
## 167105338 ./data/en_US/en_US.twitter.txt

The files are 900000 to 2.4 million lines, with around 200 million characters each. The entries in the blogs and news datasets are pretty similar. They have around 230 and 200 characters per entry, respectively. The entries in the Twitter dataset are much shorter, at 70 character per entry, on average, which is somewhat expected, since Tweets were limited to 140 characters maximum.

To look at the content in more detail, we use the tm package. Since the files are relatively large, I created subsets of each one with 10000 lines. Since these were randomly chosen, they will be representative of the dataset as a whole.

After loading the contents of this subsetting dataset into a corpus, we perform some transformations to get it into a more useful form. We remove all numbers and punctuation, and put everything into lower case. It may be useful to bring some of these things back for the final model, but they would only obfuscate our exploratory analysis.

vc <- VCorpus(DirSource("/home/rumbaugh/Coursera-Swiftkey/data/en_US/all_10000/"), readerControl = list(language='lat'))
vc <- tm_map(vc, removeNumbers)
vc <- tm_map(vc, removePunctuation)
vc <- tm_map(vc, stripWhitespace)
vc <- tm_map(vc, content_transformer(tolower))
vc_noSW <- tm_map(vc, removeWords, stopwords("english"))
vcDTM <- DocumentTermMatrix(vc)
vc_noSWDTM <- DocumentTermMatrix(vc_noSW)

Another transformation commonly used for NLP applications is to remove stopwords, which are very common words like “the”, “and”, or “you”. It’s highly likely we will want to build our model to include these words, so we will branch off the analysis here, with one branch including stopwords and one having them removed. This also allows us to better see the differences between the news, blogs, and Tweets, as well.

We create a document term matrix for the datasets with and without stopwords. These are matrices with one row for each of the three files that went into our analysis, and each column having the frequency that a specific word appears in that file.

The news stories tend to focus on words relevant to reporting, like “said” or numbers like “one” or “two”, as well as words pertaining to when and where like “year” and “state”. Tweets seem to focus on words related to more personal interactions or expressing yourself, such as “love”, “good”, “thanks”, and talking about how your “day” went. The common words in the Blog entries seem to be a combination of the qualities of news and Tweets, which could reflect their more personal style compared to news articles, but also the wide range of topics covered.

Rather than look at how often some specific words are used, we can also look at the distribution of how often all words are used.

grid.arrange(countshist, counts_noSWhist, ncol=2)

In the above plots, the y-axis is the frequency with which a word is used in a document. The x-axis shows how many words are used with that frequency. For example, the smallest bin represents words used only once within the document, and there are around 100,000 of those in the Twitter file. Note that the axes are on a logarithmic scale to better show the range here, since there are orders of magnitude more common words than uncommon words.

For both the cases with and without stopwords, there are many words used just a few times. Around 100,000 words used just once which drops off to a still high 10,000 when you get to words used around 10 times in a document. At the high end, there are only on the order of 10 words used 1000 times or more, which is a bit higher when stopwords are included. Overall, the distributions are very similar between the different documents, dropping off exponentially as the frequency of the words used decreases, and without a large effect when stopwords are removed.

N-grams

An important part of this analysis will be constructing N-grams and predicting the next word in a given N-gram. In our case, an N-gram is an ordered sequence of N words. We will look at the distributions of bigrams (N = 2) and trigrams (N = 3). We will construct new document term matrices for both of these cases, also with and without stopwords.

BigramTokenizer <- function(x) NGramTokenizer(x, Weka_control(min = 2, max = 2))
TrigramTokenizer <- function(x) NGramTokenizer(x, Weka_control(min = 3, max = 3))

vc_bigram_tdm <- DocumentTermMatrix(vc, control = list(tokenize = BigramTokenizer))
vc_trigram_tdm <- DocumentTermMatrix(vc, control = list(tokenize = TrigramTokenizer))
vc_bigram_tdm_noSW <- DocumentTermMatrix(vc_noSW, control = list(tokenize = BigramTokenizer))
vc_trigram_tdm_noSW <- DocumentTermMatrix(vc_noSW, control = list(tokenize = TrigramTokenizer))

These plots are constructed in the same way as before, with the x-axis representing the frequency of a given bigram or trigram, and the y-axis showing how many bigrams or trigrams had that frequency within a document. Like the distributions for single words, the frequencies drop off exponentially. Since we are now looking at unique permutations of two or three words, there are a lot fewer compared to single words, which is reflected in only a handful bigrams having frequencies of 1000 or higher, and just a few trigrams having frequencies above 100, when including all words.

However, stopwords have a large effect on N-grams, as there is a marked difference between the top and bottom panels. The high end on the x-axis drops off by an order of magnitude when stopwords are removed. There are now only a few bigrams with frequencies above 100 or trigrams with frequencies above 10. This shows stopwords are imporant for constructing N-grams, and thus for building our models.

Dictionary Coverage

There are a large number of words that appear only once in our dataset. Many of these will not be particularly useful for constructing our models, and we could more efficiently build those models with a smaller input set of words and N-grams. So, it could be useful to look at how well the top N most common words cover the total size of the dataset.

grid.arrange(percplot, percplot_noSW, ncol=2)

These plots show how many of the top N most common words you need to include to cover a given percentage of a document. The x-axis is fraction of the document covered. For example, 0.1 on the x-axis means that a dictionary included 10% of the total words in a document (including repeats). The y-axis shows what percentage of words, starting with the most common word and working down, you needed to include in a dictionary to cover that. The axes are shown on logarithmic scales to better show the range. The vertical lines are at 50% and 90% (0.5 and 0.9) on the x-axis.

Looking at the results, the trends are very similar for the different documents, and between the cases with and without stopwords. 50% coverage is achieved using around 1% of the most common words with stopwords included, and a few percent higher when they aren’t. Only around 20% or 30% of the most common words are needed to cover 90% of the total document size with and without including stopwords, respectively.

Conclusions

Our dataset consists of entries from three sources: blogs, news articles, and Twitter. Looking length of these entries and their most common words, there are a number of differences between them. Tweets are shorter and tend to use more personal language, for example. These differences will complement each other when building a prediction algorithm, since they cover different parts of language. Because the Tweets are shorter overall, it may be necessary to put weights on the different datasets so that they are adequately represented in our models.

Looking at the distributions of the frequencies of words in the documents, it became clear that including stopwords is important, especially when considering N-grams. Since N-grams will be the basis of our models, it is necessary to include them, or otherwise miss out on an order of magnitude of unique N-grams in the documents.

We also showed that the analysis can be simplified by filtering the dataset through a dictionary that contains only the most common words. Only the 20% most common words are needed to cover 90% of the total content in the documents. This may be too few to consider, but it does mean we probably don’t have to consider words that appear only a few times in the entire dataset, which would simplify our models considerably.

The next step in this project is to begin constructing models that predict the the next word in an N-gram based on the (N-1)-gram. We have some strategies for simplifying this model construction. I will start building these models using Markov chains, which assign probabilities to the next word in any N-gram based on the (N-1) word before it.
